	<td class="thead">
	
	<!-- 2 -->
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		
		<td class="smallfont"><b></b></td>
		<td class="smallfont" align="right" wrap="nowrap">Post #<b><a href="showpost.php?s=2e54227d1511ddf4d6237ffb1f4fb39a&amp;postid=141928&postcount=16" target="new">16</a></b></td>
	</tr>
	</table>
	<!-- /2 -->
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Loramin</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: May 2002<br />
	Location: California, USA
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Ok, I need to explain a few things.  First off, I never meant to portray anything as "truth" unless it was widely regarded to be such by the Everquest community.  It is accepted truth, for example, that Verant's standard line on specialization is that it involves checks.  My point wasn't to say that Verant was telling the truth, I just wanted to give all sides of the story, ie. "VI says this, but most people believe this".   As I explained in my post, Caster's Realm is frequently incorrect about things, and they tend to err on the side of old info or official Verant info.  This is why I quoted the "truthful" information from Graffes, which as I admitted still had the possibility of being out of date.<br />
<br />
At this point, I departed from accepted "truth" and went off on my own speculations.  The fact that these were merely my speculations must have escaped you Jharassik, but I appreciate the support of people like FilurGlamrist, who understood that I prefaced almost all of my statements with cautionary warnings such as "the second possibility" or "by this logic" or "if that's true" or "seems far more likely".  However, I admit I maybe should have included such a warning before my "short answer," or perhaps not given it at all.  However, I've noticed people tend to like to have a short answer given first, with an explanation of why the author thinks it afterwards (BTW, I got this habit from academic journal papers, which begin with a summary paragraph explaining the gist of the paper's argument).<br />
<br />
Anyhow, now that more people have posted, we have a lot more data, and some of my original ideas have been shown to be incorrect.  /Shrug.  Glad someone else was able to do in-game research, I had to rely on the web because the server was down and no one I knew who played EQ was on AIM.  Still, I stand by my assertation that someone should compile the information that is considered to be true, and put it in the Crucible tips.<br />
<br />
Since I'm a someone, I'll start a first draft:<br />
<br />
"<b>How does specialization work?</b><br />
<br />
Well, there's two school's of thought on this: Verant's, and the correct one.  The school of thought proposed by Verant, and outlined/explained at "http://eq.crgaming.com/misc/pages/special.asp" is that specialization is a set of skills, one of which is invoked every time you cast a spell (once you've reached the appropriate level, 30 for shaman), and depending on which spells you cast the most, one school will eventually reach a higher skill (200) than the others, which will cap at (50).  So far so good.<br />
<br />
Then we get to the incorrect part.  Verant claims that when you cast a spell the computer makes a roll, and depending on your specialization skill you may or may not "succeed" at the roll.  If you do succeed, then your spell will have reduced mana cost, and fizzle rate.<br />
<br />
However, many dutiful parsers and users of ShowEQ have diligently run tests to determine how specialization, and the conclusions they came up with are summed up nicely at "http://www.graffe.com/graffe1.0/lib...izardly_faq.htm" (under section "2. Spells").  In brief, they determined that there is no roll for specialization, and in fact that it simply works all the time.  For your primary (skill 200) specialization, you save 10% mana on all spells you cast from that school.  For your secondary (50) skills you get a 2.5% reduction in mana cost.<br />
<br />
To their credit, Caster's Realm does have a few useful points on Specialization:<br />
<br />
"Specialisation does not increase chance of recovering after interruption.  This is based purely on Channelling.  Specialisation does not make spells cast faster.  This is a fixed amount."<br />
<br />
<b>But what about Spell Casting Mastery (SCM)?</b><br />
<br />
According to Verant, the AAXP skill Spell Casting Mastery works as follows (borrowed from Caster's Realm):<br />
<br />
"[SCM ] increases the chance that a player will successfully get a specialization roll.  The first point increases the chance of specialization by 5%, the second raises the chance to 15% and the third to 30%."<br />
<br />
However, as we already know there are no specialization checks in Everquest, so how does this ability really work?  Well, according to reports from The Crucible, SCM:3 adds 10% reduction to all spells cast.  However, one report from Hannduvdeth showed that for him, one casting of Khura's Focusing MGB style 51%, as opposed to 44% after SCM3.  This would only seem to indicate a savings of 7%, so assuming Hannduvdeth has his specialization(alteration) maxxed at 200 (a fairly safe assumption) there might be as much as a 3% loss, possibly only on MGB spells.  Then again this 3% difference might have come from equipment changes in Hann's gear in between his getting the skill as well.  The moral of this story is that SCM3 probably gives 10% to all castings, including MGB, but your mileage may vary :-)<br />
<br />
Now, what about SCM2 and SCM1?  We don't have any hard figures on this, but if you assume that these skills follow the same progression as Verant claims they do (5/15/30), then SCM1 gives about 1.7% savings, and SCM2 gives 5%.  However, to date there have been no tests done (on the Crucible, that I know of; if anyone knows of info from another board feel free to post a link and/or quote it)."<br />
<br />
Edit/Critique/Review/Criticize away <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /></p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Loramin Frostseer<br />
(65 Barbarian Prophet on the Bristlebane server)<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=219744&amp;resize=true"  target="_new">Click here for character info</a></div>
	
