<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Demisius</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: May 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>So since we're trying to nail things down, the one "Variable" we still have is mana preservation, which is between 1 and 10% mana reduction and Affliction efficiency which is between 1 and 25%.   Most people that I've talked to thought that it was flat 10/25% savings.  But on *average* mana preservation is 5.5% mana savings, and AE to 13%.  <br />
<br />
<br />
Here's my logic behind it since I'm bored at work :P<br />
<br />
User casting 1 spell 10 times.   First time the MP item reduced the mana usage by 1, second time by 2, third time by 3 etc etc.<br />
<br />
Adding up the percentages of mana saved, you get 1+2+3+4...+10 = 55<br />
Divide by the number of casts to get the Average Percentage of mana saved   <br />
55/10 = 5.5<br />
<br />
While this scenario will rarely be true for any 10 casts, when averaged out over a long period of time it should become statistically equivilent  (or something like that).<br />
<br />
Assumptions:<br />
- Amount of mana saved by the MP item is not weighted, as in 1 will occur as frequently as 10 over a large enough sample.<br />
- I didn't make any typo's while entering my numbers :P<br />
<br />
This doesn't nail things down as it's an average, but it gave me a much better picture of how much my MP item was helping.   5.5% of a 4k mana pool is around 200 mana saved when going from FM->OOM.<br />
<br />
<br />
PS: Does the process of 10+9+8....+1 Have a name?  It's not factorial which is 10*9*8*7..*1</p>
	
	
	
	
	
